<span id="freeTextContainer3152459054716243326"><b>Monstrous virtuosity, an expanding universe, world without end... </b><br/><br/>Reading Carlos Fuentes’ Terra Nostra sometimes feels like gazing at the Sistine Chapel, or one of Bosch’s triptychs. The sheer amount of and attention to detail overwhelms the singularity of its creation, to the point where only the mosaic itself is visible. It appears almost inhuman and alien, out of bounds for human creativity, a novel driven by the same force that drove Dante’s Ulysses beyond the pillars of Hercules. But readin</span>
  <span id="freeText3152459054716243326" style="display:none"><b>Monstrous virtuosity, an expanding universe, world without end... </b><br /><br />Reading Carlos Fuentes’ Terra Nostra sometimes feels like gazing at the Sistine Chapel, or one of Bosch’s triptychs. The sheer amount of and attention to detail overwhelms the singularity of its creation, to the point where only the mosaic itself is visible. It appears almost inhuman and alien, out of bounds for human creativity, a novel driven by the same force that drove Dante’s Ulysses beyond the pillars of Hercules. But reading it again, slowly, and I mean very slowly, the seams stitching everything together emerge; the flawlessness of its design is vastly overshadowed by the intricacy of its composite elements. <br /><br />Part historical novel and part mythological retelling of the Spanish Empire, Terra Nostra is a chaosmos which uncovers a Viconian cycle of history with El Escorial as its birthplace and its grave, but it is a novel that cannot be reduced to a simple cycle of viciousness; tragically so. Let me explain.<br /><br />At the beginning of the end of the third of the book’s three parts, we find an old knight with creaking bones and a broken sword inside a windmill. He was not always this way, he tells us, he was in fact once young and in love, but his beloved Dulcinea was killed by her father and he in turn by our Knight of the Sorrowful Countenance. He fled, he confesses, to a village whose name he does not wish to recall,<br /><br />“’alone, knowing in my flesh the truth of what the old procuress who furnished me Dulcinea’s favors had told me: old age is a hostelry of illness, an inn for thoughts, unremitting anguish, incurable wound, stain of the past, pain of the present, morose concern for the future, neighbor to death, and, standing as tall as possible in the cart and raising his lance as if to wound the clouds, he said, books were my only consolation, I read them all, I imagined I could be one of those flawless knights, rescue those illustrious ladies, vanquish those perfidious giants and magicians...”<br /><br />He returns to the gravestone of his beloved and her father, wishing to make amends, but instead of forgiveness he is met by a curse. The statue of Dulcinea’s father condemns him to something worse than hell, that his reading would become reality, that his fragile body would actually face giants and monsters, only visible to him, to be mocked, caged, taken for a madman. <br /><br />The knight accepts the curse. He fights monsters disguised as windmills and armies dressed as sheep until his squire abandons him: <br /><br />“But see what my fate has been, sirs, that I see the truth of things which others hold to be a lie; the enchantment lay upon the others; and greater the enchantment of my enchantment, as I saw that only I, cursed by the statue of Dulcinea’s father, saw giants where others, as if enchanted, saw only windmills [...]. But do you know what my revenge will be? I shall declare that my reason has returned. I shall keep my secret. I shall accept that everything I have seen is a lie. I shall try to convince no one.”<br /><br />To Fuentes, fiction may very well be a mirror of the world, but a mirror which only reflects back darkly. Fuentes demands of his readers to consider the blasphemous implications of reading itself; to imagine a world of fiction as boundless as reality but constrained within the limitations of the pages. Reality is a sick dream, as he writes elsewhere, but if that it so, then reading is a nightmare without end. Fuentes’ triptych is a landscape in which<br /><br />“anything is possible; nothing must be rejected; nature, and in particular human nature, encompasses each and every level of existence, from the divine to the diabolic, from the bestil to the mystic; nothing is beyond belief; nothing is beyond possibility; the only possibilities we deny are the possibilities we do not know...”<br /><br />What possibilities, say? A baby girl born in the stable of Bethlehem, Pilate condemning Barabbas to die on the cross, Socrates refusing the temptation of suicide, an Odysseus who never made it out of Troy, the Trojan horse consumed by flames, Helen returned home, Job fleeing his, Abel forgotten by Cain, Antigone submitting to the law, Lucifer restored, Noah’s ark sinking. No, one cycle is already too much to bear.<br /><br />It is a novel that covers so much material that it seems suspicious, if not downright implausible, that it can be contained within the constricts of a book bound in paper and glue. But then again, as El Senor repeats over and over, we must trust only what is written. I stand by my original statement, that this novel is not just one of the greatest of the twentieth century, a century of so many great novels, but one of the greatest in human history, a virtuoso at the peak of his powers constructing, stone for stone, one monstrous theology of brutality. Please read this; it won't make you a better person, but if it doesn't make you a better reader then you're reading wrong.</span>
