<span id="freeTextContainer5516419206688402628">If not for Proust, this would have probably counted as my yearly entry into the inadvertently created category, &quot;Giant Works of Foreign Literature&quot;. And while the length is almost adorably petite compared to some of the stuff I&apos;ve been reading in this past year (seven hundred pages? that&apos;s like a long weekend at this point!), much like a lot of the other Giant Books, this one goes out of its way to prove that you don&apos;t acquire the ambition to craft a massive era spanning novel without also simul</span>
  <span id="freeText5516419206688402628" style="display:none">If not for Proust, this would have probably counted as my yearly entry into the inadvertently created category, "Giant Works of Foreign Literature". And while the length is almost adorably petite compared to some of the stuff I've been reading in this past year (seven hundred pages? that's like a long weekend at this point!), much like a lot of the other Giant Books, this one goes out of its way to prove that you don't acquire the ambition to craft a massive era spanning novel without also simultaneously acquiring the skills to not write like a normal person. However, it's not like he wrote it backwards or anything. More like sideways.<br /><br />Carlos Fuentes is one of those amazingly admired and lauded writers that most of us here have never heard of, mostly because he's Mexican and the majority of his books are written in Spanish. His best known novel is "The Death of Artemio Cruz" (which I have in the queue around here somewhere), and he was one of those perpetual wallflowers for the Nobel Prize for Literature, sadly not winning before his passing in 2012. "Terra Nostra" is probably by far his longest and most complicated book, a dense brick of a novel that attempts to deal with centuries of history on two continents and convey that to us in the most obtuse manner possible, making it kind of alternate between dazzling and frustrating, like watching a toddler successfully competing in a contest to complete your taxes as swiftly as possible, but who keeps getting distracted by bouncy balls.<br /><br />The novel is divided into three parts, "The Old World", "The New World" and "The Next World", all of which signify exactly what you'd expect them to be. The main story seems to exist as stories within stories, as an encounter in the present day takes us back to the reign of the Spanish king Philip II (though I think we meet his similarly named father first, charmingly, both are called "El Senor"), carrying us through the son's attempts to build what eventually becomes the El Escorial even as he physically declines and all kinds of weird mystical things happen that may have to do with the New World and may have more to do with the fact that Fuentes ladles on great heaping doses of magical realism, which is just another way of him tapping you on the shoulder and whispering gently into your ear, "Just go with it".<br /><br />Paging through my volume for this, I also just realized that there's a extremely helpful character guide in the very beginning, which I suggest you avail yourself of. It would have saved me some confusion.<br /><br />The vast chunk of the novel is spent in the court of Philip II and having a decent working knowledge of Spanish history and mythology will be extremely beneficial to you here, as Fuentes doesn't believe in separating reality from fantasy. His prose is (with some credit to the translator) amazing and he's not afraid to experiment with narration and perception, meaning that some chapters are written in a shifting, first person style while others are simply narrated and others convey related stories that don't tie into the plot until later. This adds a rather kaleidoscopic view to the proceedings that can be rather dizzying at times. Fuentes' prose can be fairly detailed and dense, something that isn't helped by the fact that he must have sneaked a clause into his contract that allows him to be paid by the semi-colon, giving you the gift of chapters that are block after block after block of monolithic paragraphs that just pile onto themselves without a break, something that can be wearying over the course of several hundred pages.<br /><br />Yet sticking with it does give you ample rewards, as every frustrating passage seems to give way into passages that are absolutely stunning in their construction and content, dealing with history and mythology and philosophy and the human heart almost simultaneously, a balancing act that's quite exciting to behold. Not a student of Spanish history I can't tell how much of this is based on actual recorded facts but even if a tenth of it is simply made up then you still have some absolutely bonkers sequences, with massacres and moving paintings and a woman who lets all her limbs die because when she falls down only her husband is allowed to touch her, and he's already dead. As dear Felipe becomes more and more obsessed with the afterlife, things start to get pleasingly insane and almost Grand Guignol in their content, graphic in its sexuality and violence. There's an almost claustrophobic nature to the proceedings, as if the characters are completely trapped in this maze of a novel, something that is only exacerbated when characters from stories start to appear as real people (Don Juan in particular, although He Who Tilts At Windmills get several memorable scenes toward the end) and everyone is being dragged toward the finish line unwillingly, especially since it seems that they're heading either toward their own demises or being forced to do it all over again.<br /><br />In that sense, the "New World" sequence of the novel is almost like a palette cleanser, telling the story of twins or triplets that may be linked to Christianity, how one goes to the faraway land of Central America (or Mexico) and runs into their mythologies and religions, giving us a heady dose of old gods and shape changing people and eternal romance, sketching out the connections between the new and old worlds while treating us to even more bizarre and magical events that your last fantasy trilogy had over its entire run. By treating everything as real, the novel gains power in suggesting that the past is just as dangerous as the future and how what we believe is just as important as what is actual. It also reminds you how deeply strange all this mythology is.<br /><br />And before long its back to the old world so we can experience the "Next World" as the book reels back and forth in history, as the characters rummage through their own pasts and the pasts that are still to come even as the current world seems intent on crumbling to pieces. Fuentes drags in the present day and links to all the fargone tomorrows that the characters fear, pulling in some truly horrific scenes but also some amazingly touching sequences, never losing control of himself for a moment even as the book threatens to lose us time and again. You can almost feel the sweat coming off his brow as he tries to keep it all tied into the theme and bring it all together, although by the time the story once again detours so we can get a tale of the Roman Empire, you're getting near to begging him to get to the point already. Its hard to even comment on the plot because its so intertwined with the message and the theme that all you can do is either let yourself get swept up in the rush, carried along as the story dances from character to character and situation to situation (its best moments often deal with Felipe and the weird royal family, but only because they're among the most concrete and understandable), especially the entanglements of who is sleeping with who and who has history with who. In some measure it's like gathering a handful of sand on the beach and attempting to weave all those disparate grains into a single coherent tale, something that Fuentes isn't quite successful at.<br /><br />Robert Coover, no stranger to giant books about esoteric topics, once wrote that if the book was a failure, it was a magnificent failure and that probably is the most apt way to describe the book. Individual scenes are among the best I've ever read in a novel but the steady accumulation of them doesn't quite add up in the way that Fuentes wants them to and before long the constant onslaught becomes numbing, especially with how dense some of the chapters are. Even if I don't have any emotional connection to Spanish and Mexican history, that doesn't stop other writers from forging connections to places I've never been to either, like realms of elves. Its a book that's amazing and dazzling and astounding and all those other superlatives in terms of pure prose and construction and thematic ambition. There is probably nothing out there quite like it and probably never will be. But there's so much thrown into the pot here, so much history and religion and drama that it becomes this great onrushing wave that extends from one side of your periphery to the other. And as much as I want to stand there and take it, the truth is when waves hit me, one of two things happen. I either am overwhelmed and die a horrifying death by drowning, or I spend all of my time trying to keep my head over water, and never quite notice how blue and beautiful that water really is.</span>
