<span id="freeTextContainer15835308816356592902"><b>Like reading Shakespeare as your first English Language Novel</b><br/><br/>Terra Nostra, written by Carlos Fuentes and almost a Spanish classic, is Metaphor rich, like existing in a living dream. There are sweeping panoramic changes in view. And, actual events are taken out of their historical sequence and combined with phantasmagoric events. With the use of the pronoun ‘Our’ in Our Earth (the title) – Fuentes is speaking directly to and about the Hispanic world.<br/><br/>In the opening sequence, a young man named Poll</span>
  <span id="freeText15835308816356592902" style="display:none"><b>Like reading Shakespeare as your first English Language Novel</b><br /><br />Terra Nostra, written by Carlos Fuentes and almost a Spanish classic, is Metaphor rich, like existing in a living dream. There are sweeping panoramic changes in view. And, actual events are taken out of their historical sequence and combined with phantasmagoric events. With the use of the pronoun ‘Our’ in Our Earth (the title) – Fuentes is speaking directly to and about the Hispanic world.<br /><br />In the opening sequence, a young man named Pollo falls into the River Seine and washes ashore on the beach of 16th Century Spain as a different character. Though it opens there in Paris, France, the shift to Spain is the locale of most of the action in the book. Some of it takes place in pre-Columbian Mexico, and some in the time of Tiberius Caesar in the first century AD. These places can be seen in the named parts of the book; The Old World, The New World, and The Next World. <br /><br /><br />The novel is truly Iberian in its nature; encompassing Spain and all of Latin American culture in its plot. But, there seems to be a huge chasm between the two (besides the Atlantic.) The Old World and the New World are seen as separate worlds. And, then there is the world he sees in the future. Fuentes believes that all Hispanic cultural and political history can be summed up in the 16th Century Spanish Empire. In El Escorial Palace &amp; Monastery we see the fact expressed both literally in the book and physically in the architecture that the Church and State live together in the Spanish world. He thinks the Latin world diverged in the discovery of the New World, yet in the future they will join in harmony.<br /><br /><br />Fuentes often uses a staccato rhythm of writing in a pleasing manner: <br /><blockquote>“Silvery webs in gardens and pantheons. Gilded webs on the smooth ceiling of the apartment in the Hôtel du Pont-Royal. The red suite. Flaming velvet. Outside, the snow is a melted standard and the river the lion rampant of the banner. Inside, white stucco. Vines. Cornucopias. Cherubs. Plaster sculpture. Red velvet and white plaster. Mirrors. Stained. Spotted with age.”</blockquote> <br /><br /><br />It is close to impossible to form an opinion of Fuentes’ ability to construct characters from Terra Nostra alone, for he seems to have not created a single character in this book. Instead he uses a number of actual historical characters, depicted in an askew manner to represent archetypes. The collage of images presented in each of the major characters makes every single one seem schizophrenic, and they are, because like actors in a low-budget play, no one portrays a single person.<br /><br /><br />The most important historical persons: <br />•	Felipe the Fair, Archduke Philip of Austria, King Philip I of Spain for several months before his death (1478-1506)<br />•	Felipe, also called El Señor, Philip II the king of Spain from 1556 to 1598 (Lived 1527-1598),<br />•	Isabel called La Señora, Elizabeth I (1533-1603), queen of England from 1558 to 1603 <br />•	Joanna Regina (1479-1555) the widow of Felipe the Fair<br />•	Tiberius Caesar, the emperor of Rome from 14 to 37 c.e<br /><br />The main characters of Terra Nostra are Felipe, his secretary Guzmán, his wife, Isabel, and his mother, Joanna, the Mad Lady. El Senor, Felipe, wants to live forever, but he doesn’t want to accept change. The Mad Lady (his Mother) seems to fear change. His wife seems to try to seize the day, living only in the moment.<br /><br /><br />But, these characters are not all. If you have watched the first Shrek movie (Disney) then you understand how the movie combines references to a multitude of pre-existing characters from children’s tales. Fuentes uses this same tactic, introducing a variety of characters and authors from Hispanic literature - even Cervantes is used. I especially enjoyed the 4 characters playing cards near the end, though I’d not read their books. They seem to be arguing over which one had the best/worst hand dealt to them, as a comedic twist. <br /><br /><br />And, here is where Fuentes excels in this book. His ability to ‘hold the mirror’ before his reader in a manner similar to the Biblical prophets makes you wonder if he’s having a laugh at your expense. Regardless of whether he’s laughing or not, he seems to have an almost bleak view, despite the harmony of worlds with which he ends. Maybe it is the past that he turns to throughout this tome that is his shelter from the messed up world he sees us living in today. He definitely sees time as cyclic.<br /><br /><br /><blockquote>Martians and Venusians have not invaded us, rather heretics and monks from the fifteenth century, conquistadors and painters from the sixteenth century, poets and entrepreneurs from the seventeenth century, philosophers, and revolutionaries from the eighteenth century, courtesans and social climbers from the nineteenth century: we have been occupied by the past.</blockquote><br /><br /><br />Fuentes presented the Hispanic world in a saltshaker of sorts. From this saltshaker, he sprinkled out the Roman Empire, the Spanish Empire, and the pre-Columbian Mexicans in the jungles of the Americas. He makes an attempt to end in harmony in the city of Lights… Paris. It’s tempting to ask why Fuentes ends in Paris. But, that is really the wrong question, because the real question is why he began in Paris. But, the Latin American problems with overpopulation and death can be implied from the metaphorically rich scenes that take place in Paris in the beginning and end of Fuentes’ novel. <br /><br /><br />As to the question of why Fuentes chose Paris for the start and end of the book. His answer is finally revealed in the last chapter.<br /><br /><br /><blockquote>Perhaps Paris was the exact moral, sexual, and intellectual point of balance between the two worlds that tear us apart: the Germanic and the Mediterranean, the North and the South, the Anglo-Saxon and the Latin.</blockquote><br /><br /><br />But, more than that, Fuentes wants the Hispanic world to see itself, like looking into a mirror. He uses this metaphor of a mirror quite a bit. And, of course he points to all the mirrors in Paris.<br /><br /><br /><blockquote>Paris seems much larger than it really is because of the infinite number of mirrors that duplicate its true space: Paris is Paris, plus its mirrors.</blockquote><br /><br /><br />Should you read this monumental work? <br />Terra Nostra is a great work, definitely and Fuentes is a genius to have come up with so much metaphor in such a scope of history. But, because of that there are constraints you should be aware of up front before deciding whether it is for you. I got sucked in first by the incredible narrator's voice of Walter Krochmal. It sounds incredible to listen to the man speak! But, I splurged to add Kindle e-text whisper-sync, because you definitely need to see the words to follow the ideas. <br /><br /><br />Also, you will most likely find it necessary to back-read some of the history of the events that take place in the book to 'get' the metaphors he dishes out in heavy doses. Being a North American, having some events turned into metaphor and changing actual historical events (like having Elizabeth marry Philip) can cause you to do a double-take in surprise at first. <br /><br /><br />Thirdly, the book can be quite graphic and explicit in some of its metaphor. To give an example of both the tame and the explicit, <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[I felt the beginning thread of the old lady giving birth, devolving in a dream like sequence of all the women of France giving birth on the streets to be a tame and intriguing metaphor for the birth of the New World. A bit later though, 'El Senor' finds some really disgusting things in his bed upon awaking, and thinks God brought that upon him, when actually his enemies brought an animal to give birth in his bed while he was passed out. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br /><br />So, yes... a bit graphic at points and shocking in some of the metaphors. It reveals some of the extremes of the Spanish Catholic mindset of that era. And, it took me almost 2 months to finish it, since I read it at a slow pace. It is only about 45 or so hours of actual reading, but re-reading parts, and back-reading to ‘get it’ added to the research time makes it quite an investment of time. And, it is my first of Fuentes works. Being such a complex novel, reading it first of Fuentes’ books is like choosing Shakespeare for your first English language novel. But, I'm glad I discovered it.</span>
